Intro

The dataset for this project comprises quarterly arrivals from the United States to Australia, denoted as us_arrivals, from 1981 Q1 to 2012 Q3. This data is derived from the broader aus_arrivals dataset in the fpp3 library, filtered specifically for entries where the origin is the United States. The dataset provides a temporal view of the number of visitors from the US to Australia, offering insights into travel trends, seasonal patterns, and potential impacts of external factors such as economic conditions, policy changes, and global events.

Tourism is a significant economic sector for Australia, contributing substantially to its GDP. Understanding and forecasting the flow of international visitors, particularly from major source countries like the United States, is crucial for stakeholders in the tourism industry, including government agencies, airlines, hotels, and tour operators. Accurate forecasts enable better resource allocation, marketing strategies, and policy-making to enhance the tourist experience and manage the economic impact.

The primary objective of this project is to develop robust forecasting models to predict future quarterly arrivals from the United States to Australia. By leveraging various time series forecasting techniques, we aim to identify the model that best captures the underlying patterns and provides the most accurate forecasts.

Overview of Data

# filter data to specify arrivals from the US
us_arrivals <- aus_arrivals |>
    dplyr::filter(Origin == "US")

# plot the data
autoplot(us_arrivals, .vars = Arrivals) + ggtitle("US Arrivals Data") + xlab("Date") +
    ylab("Arrivals")

summary(us_arrivals$Arrivals)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   23721   63950   85878   84849  108977  136094

The data shows an increasing amount of arrivals from the US to Australia over time. The summary shows that the mean number of arrivals was 84849, with the minimum at 23721 and maximum at 136094.

ARIMA Model

# convert data to time series
us_arrivals_ts <- ts(us_arrivals$Arrivals, start = c(1981, 1), frequency = 4)

# create train/test split (for forecasts)
train <- window(us_arrivals_ts, end = c(2005, 4))
test <- window(us_arrivals_ts, start = c(2006, 1))

# plot tsdisplay
tsdisplay(us_arrivals_ts)

It seems like the data might not be stationary, so we might need to do some differencing. For the ACF plot, values are generally decreasing over time. For the PACF plot, there are significant spikes up to lag 5. Because of this, we will start by testing out an AR(5) model.

# arima model 1
arima.model1 <- arima(train, order = c(5, 0, 0))
arima.resid1 <- resid(arima.model1)
tsdisplay(arima.resid1, main = "Residuals of ARIMA AR(5)")

Box.test(arima.resid1, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  arima.resid1
## X-squared = 0.34328, df = 1, p-value = 0.5579

For the most part, there are no significant spikes in the ACF/PACF plots. Based on the Box-Ljung results for arima model 1, we can conclude that there is no autocorrelation in the residuals. This suggests that the arima model sufficiently captures the autocorrelation present in the data.

Next, we will try to improve the model by differencing the data.

# arima model 2
arima.model2 <- arima(train, order = c(5, 1, 0))
arima.resid2 <- resid(arima.model2)
tsdisplay(arima.resid2, main = " Residuals of ARIMA AR(5) with Differencing")

Box.test(arima.resid2, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  arima.resid2
## X-squared = 0.16695, df = 1, p-value = 0.6828

Again, there are barely any significant spikes in the ACF/PACF plots. Based on the Box-Ljung results, we can conclude that there is no autocorrelation in the residuals and that the arima model sufficiently captures autocorrelation in the data.

Lastly, we will try an auto arima model for comparison.

forecast.arima3 <- forecast(arima.model3, h = 27)
autoplot(train) + autolayer(forecast.arima3, series = "ARIMA(3,0,2)(0,1,1)") + autolayer(test,

Holt-Winters

us_arrivals <- aus_arrivals %>%
  dplyr::filter(Origin == "US")

test <- window(us_arrivals_ts, start = c(2006, 1))

Prophet Model

train_prophet <- aus_arrivals %>%
  dplyr::filter(Origin == "US") %>%
  dplyr::filter(as.integer(format(Quarter, "%Y")) <= 2005)

test_prophet <- aus_arrivals %>%
  dplyr::filter(Origin == "US") %>%
  dplyr::filter(as.integer(format(Quarter, "%Y")) >= 2006)

prophet_fit <- train_prophet %>%
  model(
    prophet = prophet(Arrivals ~ season(period = 4, order = 2,
                                    type = "additive"))
  )

# Use an additive model since the seasonality is relatively constant over time


prophet_forecast <- prophet_fit %>% forecast(h = 27)
prophet_forecast %>% autoplot(us_arrivals)

We decide to fit an additive prophet model of order 2 since the frequency is quarterly and the seasonality is relatively constant over time. The prophet model does not seem to fit the data very well as it predicts a continuing upward trend, although the actual data flattens out.

prophet_forecast %>% accuracy(test_prophet)

NNETAR Model

# convert data to time series
us_arrivals_ts <- ts(us_arrivals$Arrivals, start = c(1981, 1), frequency = 4)

# create train/test split (for forecasts)
train <- window(us_arrivals_ts, end = c(2005, 4))
test <- window(us_arrivals_ts, start = c(2006, 1))

arrival_nnetar <- nnetar(train)

THe NNETAR Model fit gives a NNAR(4,1,2) model. From the NNETAR model fit and the evaluation of residuals, we can see that NNETAR model gives a pretty good fit to the training data. The residuals also seems to be like white noise that is normally distributed, with p being 0.2151 in the ljung-Box test.

forecast.nnetar <- forecast(arrival_nnetar, h = 27)
autoplot(train) + autolayer(forecast.nnetar, series = "NNAR(4,1,2)") + autolayer(test,
    series = "Test Data")

Even though the model fits pretty well on the training data, the subsequent forecasts performs badly, and is very naise, most likely due to the nature of NNETAR model that eventually plateaus for this kind of data. The accuracy is also pretty bad, with RMSE reaching 10176 for the test data. This is worse than the ARIMA, ETS, and HW models, but better than the Prophet model.

Forecast Combination

For our combination model, we will average the forecasts from ETS, ARIMA, HW, and NNAR models.

#convert data to time series
us_arrivals_ts <- ts(us_arrivals$Arrivals, start = c(1981, 1), frequency = 4)

#create train/test split (for forecasts)
train <- window(us_arrivals_ts, end = c(2005,4))
test <- window(us_arrivals_ts, start = c(2006,1))

h <- length(us_arrivals_ts) - length(train)

ETS <- forecast(ets(train), h=h)
ARIMA <- forecast(auto.arima(train),
  h=h)
HW <- hw(train, seasonal = c("additive"), damped = TRUE, h = 27)
NNAR <- forecast(nnetar(train), h=h)
Combination <- (ETS[["mean"]] + ARIMA[["mean"]] + NNAR[["mean"]] + HW[["mean"]])/4

autoplot(us_arrivals_ts) +
  autolayer(ETS, series="ETS", PI=FALSE) +
  autolayer(ARIMA, series="ARIMA", PI=FALSE) +
  autolayer(NNAR, series="NNAR", PI=FALSE) +
  autolayer(HW, series = "HW", PI = FALSE) +
  autolayer(Combination, series="Combination") +
  xlab("Year") + ylab("Arrivals") +
  ggtitle("Quarterly Arrivals from the US to Australia")

Visually, the combination model seems to fit the data pretty well, but it looks like the Holt-Winters model still has the best fit.

Combination %>% accuracy(test)
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      ACF1 Theil's U
## Test set -2941.051 7383.842 5767.298 -2.933661 5.194788 0.3450797 0.5534617

The RMSE of the combined model is 7540 and the MAE is 5919, which are both higher than the Holt-Winters model we fit earlier (RMSE = 6909, MAE = 5569). However, the combined model performs the second-best among all the models we fit.

Conclusion and Future Work

Through this project, we attempted to forecast quarterly arrivals from the United States to Australia using data between 1981 Q1 and 2012 Q3. We fit seasonal ARIMA, ETS, Holt-Winters, Prophet, and NNAR models to the data, then performed a forecast combination between the ARIMA, ETS, HW, and NNAR models.

We concluded that the additive Holt-Winters model with damped trend fit the data best, having the lowest RMSE and MAE on unseen test data. This is likely because the trend of the data flattens out towards the end rather than continuing its upward growth. The combination model, which consisted of averaging the forecasts from ARIMA, ETS, HW, and NNAR, performed second-best, having an RMSE of 7540 and MAE of 5919. The other four models all performed significantly worse in the following order: NNAR(4,1,2), ETS(M,A,M), ARIMA(3,0,2)(0,1,1), then Prophet.

In the future, we could compare try to improve our combined model by changing the weights on each of the individual models. For example, it may have been better to exclude the ARIMA model and place more weight on the Holt-Winters model.
